Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis

Marks: 60

Context

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 3: Are there any missing values in the data? If yes, treat them using an appropriate method. [1 mark]

We will create a new column, 'rating_numeric,' to preserve the original 'rating' data while converting it into a numeric format.

This approach ensures the integrity of the original data and enables mathematical analysis and statistical operations on the numeric ratings.

# Helper function for standard vertical bar plot
def plot_categorical_distribution_inline(ax, column, title, xlabel, ylabel, top_n=None):
    """
    Plots a vertical bar chart for a categorical variable on a given axis.
    """
    # Get counts and percentages
    value_counts = df[column].value_counts()
    total = df[column].count()
    if top_n:
        value_counts = value_counts.head(top_n)
    percentages = (value_counts / total * 100).round(2)

    # Prepare data for visualization
    visualization_data = pd.DataFrame({
        column: value_counts.index,
        'Count': value_counts.values,
        'Percentage': percentages.values
    })

    # Plot vertical bar chart
    sns.barplot(
        ax=ax,
        x=visualization_data[column],
        y=visualization_data['Count'],
        palette=palette
    )

    # Annotate the bars
    for bar, count, pct in zip(ax.patches, visualization_data['Count'], visualization_data['Percentage']):
        ax.annotate(
            f"{pct}%",
            (bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, bar.get_height() + 1),
            ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=12, color='black'
        )

    # Customize the chart
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=16)
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=12)
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=12)
    ax.tick_params(axis='x')

# Helper function for horizontal bar plot
def plot_categorical_distribution_inline_horizontal(ax, column, title, xlabel, ylabel, top_n=None):
    """
    Plots a horizontal bar chart for a categorical variable on a given axis.
    """
    # Get counts and percentages
    value_counts = df[column].value_counts()
    total = df[column].count()
    if top_n:
        value_counts = value_counts.head(top_n)
    percentages = (value_counts / total * 100).round(2)

    # Prepare data for visualization
    visualization_data = pd.DataFrame({
        column: value_counts.index,
        'Count': value_counts.values,
        'Percentage': percentages.values
    })

    # Plot horizontal bar chart
    sns.barplot(
        ax=ax,
        y=visualization_data[column],
        x=visualization_data['Count'],
        palette=palette,
        orient='h'
    )

    # Annotate the bars
    for bar, count, pct in zip(ax.patches, visualization_data['Count'], visualization_data['Percentage']):
        ax.annotate(
            f"{pct}%",
            (bar.get_width() + 1, bar.get_y() + bar.get_height() / 2),
            ha='left', va='center', fontsize=12, color='black'
        )

    # Customize the chart
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=16)
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=12)
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=12)

def analyze_cost_of_the_order(focus_range=None):
    """
    Analyzes the 'cost_of_the_order' variable in the dataset.
    Provides a histogram, boxplot, and violin plot for the entire variable.
    Optionally highlights data within a specified range and performs a deeper analysis.

    Args:
    - focus_range (tuple, optional): A tuple specifying a range (min, max) for further analysis.
    """

    # Summary statistics for the filtered data
    mean_val = df['cost_of_the_order'].mean()
    median_val = df['cost_of_the_order'].median()
    std_dev = df['cost_of_the_order'].std()
    print(f"Summary Statistics for 'cost_of_the_order':")
    print(f"Mean: {mean_val:.2f}")
    print(f"Median: {median_val:.2f}")
    print(f"Standard Deviation: {std_dev:.2f}\n")

    # General analysis
    print(f"Analyzing 'cost_of_the_order' for the entire dataset...\n")
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))

    # Histogram
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
    sns.histplot(
        df['cost_of_the_order'], kde=True, bins='auto', color='lightpink'
    )
    plt.title("Histogram of cost_of_the_order", fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel("cost_of_the_order", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel("Frequency", fontsize=12)

    # Boxplot
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
    sns.boxplot(
        x=df['cost_of_the_order'], color='lightblue'
    )
    plt.title("Boxplot of cost_of_the_order", fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel("cost_of_the_order", fontsize=12)

    # Violin Plot
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
    sns.violinplot(
        x=df['cost_of_the_order'], color='lavender'
    )
    plt.title("Violin Plot of cost_of_the_order", fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel("cost_of_the_order", fontsize=12)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    # Focused range analysis
    if focus_range:
        print(f"\nAnalyzing values within range {focus_range} for 'cost_of_the_order'...\n")

        # Filter data within the specified range
        filtered_df = df[(df['cost_of_the_order'] >= focus_range[0]) & (df['cost_of_the_order'] <= focus_range[1])]

        # Handle case when no data is found in the range
        if filtered_df.empty:
            print(f"No data found in the range {focus_range}.")
            return

        print(f"Number of occurrences in range {focus_range}: {len(filtered_df)}")

        # Summary statistics for the filtered data
        mean_val = filtered_df['cost_of_the_order'].mean()
        median_val = filtered_df['cost_of_the_order'].median()
        std_dev = filtered_df['cost_of_the_order'].std()
        print(f"Summary Statistics for 'cost_of_the_order' in range {focus_range}:")
        print(f"Mean: {mean_val:.2f}")
        print(f"Median: {median_val:.2f}")
        print(f"Standard Deviation: {std_dev:.2f}\n")

        # Re-plot Histogram for the filtered data
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
        sns.histplot(
            filtered_df['cost_of_the_order'], kde=True, bins='auto', color='lightgreen'
        )
        plt.title(f"Histogram of cost_of_the_order (Filtered Range: {focus_range})", fontsize=14)
        plt.xlabel("cost_of_the_order", fontsize=12)
        plt.ylabel("Frequency", fontsize=12)
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

def plot_discrete_variable(column, title_prefix, xlabel, ylabel, order=None, bins=None):
    """
    Plots a count plot, boxplot, and violin plot for a discrete numeric variable.
    Optionally bins the values for the count plot with whole number ranges.

    Args:
    - column (str): The name of the column to analyze.
    - title_prefix (str): Prefix for the plot titles (e.g., 'Food Preparation Time').
    - xlabel (str): Label for the x-axis.
    - ylabel (str): Label for the y-axis.
    - order (list, optional): Order for the count plot. Defaults to None.
    - bins (int, optional): Number of bins to use for the count plot. Defaults to None.
    """
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))

    # Count Plot
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
    if bins:
        # Calculate integer bin edges
        min_val = int(df[column].min())
        max_val = int(df[column].max())
        bin_edges = list(range(min_val, max_val + 1, (max_val - min_val) // bins))
        if bin_edges[-1] < max_val:  # Ensure the last bin includes the max value
            bin_edges.append(max_val)

        # Create binned data for the count plot
        binned_data = pd.cut(df[column], bins=bin_edges, include_lowest=True)
        sns.countplot(
            x=binned_data,
            data=df,
            palette=palette
        )
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)  # Rotate bins for better readability
    else:
        sns.countplot(
            x=column,
            data=df,
            order=order,
            palette=palette
        )
    plt.title(f"Count Plot of {title_prefix}", fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=12)

    # Boxplot
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
    sns.boxplot(
        x=df[column],
        color='lightblue'
    )
    plt.title(f"Boxplot of {title_prefix}", fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=12)

    # Violin Plot
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
    sns.violinplot(
        x=df[column],
        color='lavender'
    )
    plt.title(f"Violin Plot of {title_prefix}", fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=12)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Add total time column

# Find the top 5 restaurants by the number of orders
top_5_restaurants = df['restaurant_name'].value_counts().nlargest(5)

# Calculate the total number of orders
total_orders = df['restaurant_name'].value_counts().sum()

# Calculate the "rest of the restaurants"
other_orders = total_orders - top_5_restaurants.sum()

# Append the "Other Restaurants" category using pd.concat
other_restaurant_series = pd.Series({'Other Restaurants': other_orders})
top_5_restaurants_with_other = pd.concat([top_5_restaurants, other_restaurant_series])

# Calculate percentages for all categories
percentages = (top_5_restaurants_with_other / total_orders * 100).round(2)

# Combine counts and percentages into a single label
labels = [f"{count} orders\n({percent}%)" for count, percent in zip(top_5_restaurants_with_other.values, percentages)]

# Plot the top 5 restaurants + "Other Restaurants"
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(
    x=top_5_restaurants_with_other.values,
    y=top_5_restaurants_with_other.index,
    palette=palette
)

# Add text labels for counts and percentages
for i, (value, label) in enumerate(zip(top_5_restaurants_with_other.values, labels)):
    plt.text(value + 1, i, label, va='center', fontsize=10)

# Title and labels

def numerical_correlation_analysis(df):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

    # Define a pastel colormap for the heatmap
    pastel_cmap = sns.light_palette("seagreen", as_cmap=True)  # Adjust color as desired

    # Compute the correlation matrix
    correlation_matrix = df[['cost_of_the_order', 'food_preparation_time', 'delivery_time', 'rating_numeric']].corr()

    # Plot the heatmap with the pastel colormap
    sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap=pastel_cmap, fmt=".2f", linewidths=0.5)

    # Add a title
    plt.title("Correlation Heatmap of Numerical Variables", fontsize=16)
    plt.show()

def numerical_vs_categorical_analysis_grid(df):
    """
    Display relevant boxplots in a 3-column grid.

    Args:
    - df (pd.DataFrame): The dataset containing the relevant variables.

    Returns:
    - None: Displays the grid of boxplots.
    """
    relevant_pairings = [
        ('delivery_time', 'day_of_the_week'),  # Operational Efficiency
        ('cost_of_the_order', 'cuisine_type'),  # Revenue Distribution
        ('rating_numeric', 'cuisine_type')  # Customer Satisfaction Insights
    ]

    # Create a figure with 1 row and 3 columns
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(24, 8))  # 1 row, 3 columns

    # Loop through the pairings and axes
    for (num_col, cat_col), ax in zip(relevant_pairings, axes):
        sns.boxplot(data=df, x=cat_col, y=num_col, palette=palette, ax=ax)
        ax.set_title(f"Boxplot of {num_col} by {cat_col}", fontsize=14)
        ax.set_xlabel(cat_col, fontsize=12)
        ax.set_ylabel(num_col, fontsize=12)
        ax.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)

    # Adjust layout for better spacing
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def scatterplots_with_jitter(df):
    """
    Create scatterplots with jitter for delivery_time and food_preparation_time against cost_of_the_order.

    Args:
    - df (pd.DataFrame): The dataset to analyze.

    Returns:
    - None: Displays the scatterplots.
    """
    plot_config = [
        {
            'x_var': 'delivery_time',
            'title': "Scatterplot of Delivery Time vs Cost with Jitter",
            'x_label': "Delivery Time"
        },
        {
            'x_var': 'food_preparation_time',
            'title': "Scatterplot of Food Prep Time vs Cost with Jitter",
            'x_label': "Food Prep Time"
        }
    ]

    # Loop through the configurations and create scatterplots
    for config in plot_config:
        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
        sns.stripplot(
            data=df,
            x=config['x_var'], y='cost_of_the_order',
            hue='rating_numeric',
            palette='deep',
            jitter=True
        )
        plt.title(config['title'], fontsize=16)
        plt.xlabel(config['x_label'], fontsize=12)
        plt.ylabel("Cost of the Order", fontsize=12)
        plt.legend(title="Rating", fontsize=10)
        plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

def grouped_insights_grid(df):
    """
    Display barplots for average cost grouped by discrete variables in a 3-column grid.

    Args:
    - df (pd.DataFrame): The dataset to analyze.

    Returns:
    - None: Displays the grid of barplots.
    """
    discrete_vars = ['rating_numeric', 'delivery_time', 'food_preparation_time']

    # Create a figure with 1 row and 3 columns
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(24, 6))  # 1 row, 3 columns

    # Loop through the variables and axes
    for var, ax in zip(discrete_vars, axes):
        grouped_data = df.groupby(var).agg(
            avg_cost=('cost_of_the_order', 'mean')
        ).reset_index()

        # Barplot for Average Cost
        sns.barplot(data=grouped_data, x=var, y='avg_cost', palette=palette, ax=ax)
        ax.set_title(f"Average Cost by {var.replace('_', ' ').title()}", fontsize=14)
        ax.set_xlabel(var.replace('_', ' ').title(), fontsize=12)
        ax.set_ylabel("Average Cost", fontsize=12)
        ax.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)

    # Adjust layout for better spacing
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def display_top_10_table(df, top_n=10):
    """
    Generate and display a styled table of the top N restaurants by order cost.

    Args:
    - df (pd.DataFrame): The dataset containing order data.
    - top_n (int): Number of top restaurants to display (default: 10).

    Returns:
    - pd.DataFrame: DataFrame with aggregated metrics for the top N restaurants.
    """
    # Aggregate metrics for each restaurant
    restaurant_metrics = df.groupby('restaurant_name').agg(
        avg_cost=('cost_of_the_order', 'mean'),
        avg_delivery_time=('delivery_time', 'mean'),
        avg_food_prep_time=('food_preparation_time', 'mean'),
        avg_rating=('rating_numeric', 'mean'),
        sum_order_cost=('cost_of_the_order', 'sum')
    ).reset_index()

    # Sort by total sum_order_cost to identify top N
    top_restaurants = restaurant_metrics.sort_values(by='sum_order_cost', ascending=False).head(top_n)

    # Round metrics for presentation
    top_restaurants = top_restaurants.round({
        'avg_cost': 2,
        'avg_delivery_time': 2,
        'avg_food_prep_time': 2,
        'avg_rating': 2,
        'sum_order_cost': 2
    })

    # Display styled table in notebook
    styled_table = top_restaurants.style.set_table_styles(
        [{
            'selector': 'thead th',
            'props': [('background-color', '#E6E6FA'), ('font-weight', 'bold'), ('color', 'navy')]
        }]
    ).set_properties(**{
        'text-align': 'center',
        'border': '1px solid black'
    }).set_caption(f"Top {top_n} Restaurants by Order Costs")

    return styled_table

# Display the styled table in the notebook
styled_table = display_top_10_table(df, top_n=10)
styled_table

# High-Cost Order Analysis Preparation
def analyze_high_cost_orders(df, cost_range=(20, 35)):
    """
    Analyze and visualize restaurants contributing to high-cost orders.

    Args:
    - df: DataFrame containing order data.
    - cost_range: Tuple specifying the range for high-cost orders (default: $20-$35).
    """
    # Filter for high-cost orders
    high_cost_min, high_cost_max = cost_range
    df['cost_range'] = pd.cut(
        df['cost_of_the_order'],
        bins=[0, 12, 20, 35],
        labels=['Low ($512)', 'Medium ($1220)', 'High ($2035)'],
        right=True
    )

    # Group by restaurant and calculate relevant metrics
    restaurant_high_cost_stats = df.groupby(['restaurant_name', 'cost_range']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)
    restaurant_high_cost_stats['Total Orders'] = restaurant_high_cost_stats.sum(axis=1)
    restaurant_high_cost_stats['High-Cost %'] = (restaurant_high_cost_stats['High ($2035)'] /
                                                 restaurant_high_cost_stats['Total Orders']) * 100
    restaurant_high_cost_stats['Average Cost'] = df.groupby('restaurant_name')['cost_of_the_order'].mean()

    # Sort by percentage of high-cost orders
    sorted_stats = restaurant_high_cost_stats.sort_values('High-Cost %', ascending=False)
    return sorted_stats

high_cost_stats = analyze_high_cost_orders(df)

def filter_top_restaurants(stats, top_n=20, min_orders=10):
    """
    Filter top restaurants based on high-cost order percentage and total orders.

    Args:
    - stats: DataFrame containing aggregated stats for restaurants.
    - top_n: Number of top restaurants to include (default: 20).
    - min_orders: Minimum total orders required to be included.

    Returns:
    - Filtered DataFrame.
    """
    # Filter restaurants with at least `min_orders`
    filtered_stats = stats[stats['Total Orders'] >= min_orders]

    # Sort by High-Cost % and select top_n
    filtered_stats = filtered_stats.sort_values('High-Cost %', ascending=False).head(top_n)

    return filtered_stats

# Filter for top 20 restaurants with at least 10 orders

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]

In[30]:
# Define a function to calculate revenue per order
def calculate_revenue(cost):
    if cost > 20:
        return cost * 0.25  # 25% of cost
    elif cost > 5:
        return cost * 0.15  # 15% of cost
    else:
        return 0  # No charge for cost <= 5

# Apply the function to calculate revenue for each order
df['revenue'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate_revenue)

# Calculate the total revenue
total_revenue = df['revenue'].sum()

# Print the result
print(f"The total revenue generated by the company is ${total_revenue:.2f}.")

The total revenue generated by the company is $6166.30.

Observations:

  • This reinforces that revenue increases with order cost.

Conclusion and Recommendations

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]

Conclusions

  1. Operational Efficiency:

    • Most orders (approximately 89.46%) are delivered within 60 minutes, with a mean total time of 51.53 minutes, demonstrating overall efficiency in food preparation and delivery processes.
    • However, 10.54 of orders exceed 60 minutes, warranting investigation to identify delays and improve consistency.
    • Orders in the $12 range represent approximately 20.25% of total volume, making them a significant driver of overall operational performance. Ensuring timely delivery for this segment is critical to maintaining efficiency metrics.

  2. Weekend vs. Weekday Performance:

    • Deliveries are faster on weekends (22.47 minutes) compared to weekdays (28.34 minute), indicating potential weekday bottlenecks related to traffic, peak demand, or resource allocation.

  3. Revenue Distribution:

    • High-cost orders (above 20 dollars) generate more revenue due to the 25 percent commision rate, but they are less frequent compared to lower-cost orders.
    • Low-to medium-cost orders, between 5 and twenty dollars, dominate in volume and contribute significantly to overall revenue, albeit at a lower 15% commission rate. Within this range, orders priced around twelve dollars stand out, accounting for approximately 20.25% of total orders and exhibiting highly consistent pricing; mean: $12.23, standard deviation: $0.34. This price band reflects strong customer preference, reinforcing its importance as a key revenue driver.

  4. Restaurant Contribution:

    • High-cost orders are concentrated among specific restaurants, with some contributing significantly to revenue. These restaurants play a critical role in maximizing profitability.
    • Restaurants driving the $12 range orders are particularly valuable, as they cater to a large volume of customers and maintain consistent pricing patterns.

  5. Customer Satisfaction Insight:

    • The provided ratings are overwhelmingly positive, indicating high levels of customer satisfaction among those who provide feedback. However, 40% of orders remain unrated, leaving a significant portion of customer experiences unaccounted for. This gap limits the ability to gain a complete understanding of overall customer satisfaction.
    • Food preparation times are evenly distributed across the dataset, implying a consistent operational standard for food preparation.

Recommendations

  1. Improve Long-Tail Order Efficiency:

    • Investigate and address the 10.54% of orders exceeding 60 minutes to identify and resolve delays in food preparation or delivery. Analyze patterns such as restaurant-specific issues, geographic regions, or peak hours to reduce inefficiencies.

  2. Optimize Weekday Deliveries:

    • Address weekday-specific bottlenecks by investigating traffic patterns, peak demand times, or resource shortages. Redistribute delivery resources or introduce incentives for off-peak orders to improve weekday performance.

  3. Leverage Popular Price Points:

    • Focus on optimizing delivery and operational efficiency for orders in the $12 range, as they represent a significant proportion of total orders and revenue.
    • Explore targeted promotions or upselling strategies within this pricing band, encouraging customers to move into higher-cost options.

  4. Collaborate with Top-Contributing Restaurants:

    • Partner with restaurants driving high-cost orders to create premium packages or deals that encourage more high-value orders.
    • Support restaurants dominating the $12 price range by enhancing operational processes and diversifying offerings to maintain customer loyalty.
    • Integrate these offerings into a loyalty program that rewards customers for frequent high-value purchases, fostering customer retention and incentivizing repeat orders.

  5. Enhance Customer Satisfaction:

    • Introduce a targeted promotion, such as a discount on a future order or loyalty points, incentivizing customers to leave feedback. This approach not only encourages more ratings but also helps gather valuable insights into customer experiences, enabling data-driven improvements to service quality and satisfaction.

  6. Promote Weekend Offers:

    • Leverage faster weekend delivery times by promoting premium offers, discounts, or incentives to increase high-cost orders and overall revenue during weekends.
